choices.text:
acne. Once pimples showed up on my skin, I always get teased or scolded by other people. It was not a big deal at first, but it becomes increasingly bigger problem. As a teen, issues with pimples made me more conscious about my blemishes. I became afraid to go out-beautiful evenings, fun outdoor activities - because I always fear that people would stigmatize me. Gradually, I started hiding in my shell because of acne and people taunting.

Then it hit me: people can really be mean, especially if you have serious issues with pimples. Little did I know that the deeper I hide in my shell, the deeper my anxiety grows. A week later, I get more pimples, more misery, and more anxiety. I thought self confidence is the antidote to my pimples and that people who don’t have pimples suffer from lack of confidence. But I eventually realized that confidence is not for show; confidence is in doing what you have to get stuff done. Even during anxious times, you have to get things done-not just pass the time because you’re afraid.

By the time my twenties started, my skin cleared up. I became a silver setter, a Figurine, and having a better life. Because of this, I started taking things more seriously and actively, and I always look for opportunities that I can be successful. One of the things that I noticed was that people who are more confident are more successful.
